 BY MAYOWA SAMUEL Senior Pastor and founder of the Citadel Global Community Church, Lagos, Tunde Bakare has quit his ministry to pursue his ambition of becoming Nigeria’s next president after the tenure of President Muhammadu Buhari elapses in 2023. Pastor Bakare disclosed this during his valedictory speech after the Sunday service at his church, formally known as the Latter Rain Assembly. The renowned preacher had at one of his Sunday sermons in 2019, said he would be the 16th president of Nigeria and Buhari’s successor. On April 9, during a virtual meeting tagged ‘Unveiling Project 16 to Nigerians in Diaspora’, with the theme ‘The portrait of a new Nigeria’, organised by the PTB4Nigeria in diaspora group, the cleric formally declared his intention to contest for the presidency. Bakare based his intention on the country’s need of a leader who can reconcile the various ethnic and religious groups and rebuild the broken walls of federalism while maximising Nigeria’s diverse geo-economic potential. He added that the country needs a leader who understands the country’s challenges and who can unite and develop the nation. Pastor Bakare was a one-time convener of the Save Nigeria Group (SNG) and a former running mate to Buhari at the 2011 presidential elections. 